---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do Brisbane building and pest reports commonly find on older inner east properties?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "On pre-war and character timber homes in Brisbane's inner east, the most common findings are timber pest activity or evidence of past termite damage, subfloor moisture or drainage issues, roof condition items (cracked tiles, rusted box gutters, flashing deterioration), and minor structural movement such as cracked cornices or differential settling. Safety items such as missing balustrade on elevated decks, unguarded stairs, or non-compliant handrail heights are also commonly flagged. A report finding minor items is normal for older Brisbane homes and does not necessarily give a buyer grounds to terminate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I commission a pre-sale building and pest inspection before listing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A pre-sale building and pest inspection gives you advance knowledge of what a buyer's report is likely to find. You can address significant items before the campaign, which removes the risk of a late-campaign renegotiation or termination. The consideration is that in Queensland, a pre-sale report you have commissioned may need to be disclosed to buyers under the Mandatory Seller Disclosure Statement requirements if it reveals material defects, which means you lose the element of strategic surprise. Your agent and conveyancer can advise on the disclosure implications for your specific situation."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "A buyer has asked for a price reduction after their building and pest report. What are my options?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your options are: agree to a price adjustment, offer to repair the identified items before settlement, decline to negotiate and allow the buyer to proceed or exercise the building and pest condition to terminate, or seek a second opinion from another inspector on the severity of the findings. The right response depends on whether the items found are genuinely significant (structural, active termite damage) or routine maintenance items for a property of the age, and on your read of the buyer's actual position. An experienced agent can help you calibrate this response."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What must I disclose to buyers about building defects when selling in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under Queensland's Mandatory Seller Disclosure Statement (introduced under the Property Law Act 2023, commencing 1 August 2025), sellers must disclose known material facts about the property that could affect a buyer's decision. This includes known structural defects, known pest damage, and other material conditions of the property. The disclosure obligation applies to facts you know or reasonably should know, not to defects you are unaware of. The buyer's building and pest inspection is their due diligence to discover what you have not disclosed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a buyer terminate a contract based on a building and pest report in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Only if the contract includes a building and pest inspection condition. The standard REIQ residential contract includes a building and pest condition that gives the buyer a specified period (usually 7-14 days from contract date) to commission an inspection and, if the report reveals defects that are not acceptable to the buyer, to terminate the contract and receive their deposit back. Once the building and pest condition period has expired without the buyer exercising the condition, that right to terminate is no longer available."
      }
    }
  ]
};
